= \frac{-11 \cdot 100 + 16 \cdot 72}{11 \cdot 16}.

question: Calculate the highest common divisor of 572964 and 1710.
output:
We can use the Euclidean algorithm to compute the greatest common divisor of 572964 and 1710. \begin{align*}
\text{gcd}\,(572964,1710) &= \text{gcd}\,(572964-1710,1710)\\

&= \text{gcd}\,(-22,44)\\
&= \text{gcd}\,(-22,44-22)\\
&= \text{gcd}\,(-22,22)\\
\end{align*}Since the Euclidean algorithm only works when the first argument is positive, we use the property $\text{gcd}\,(a,b)=\text{gcd}\,(-a,b)$ to get $$\text{gcd}\,(-22,22)=\text{gcd}\,(22,-22).$$Continuing the Euclidean algorithm, \begin{align*}
\text{gcd}\,(22,-22) &= \text{gcd}\,(22-1\cdot (-22),-22)\\
&= \text{gcd}\,(44,-22)\\
&= \text{gcd}\,(44,22-1\cdot 44)\\
&= \text{gcd}\,(44,8)\\

&= \text{gcd}\,(8,4)\\
&= \text{gcd}\,(8-2\cdot 4,4)\\

\end{align*}Since we have $$1710=2\cdot 22\cdot 31$$and $22$ is the only common factor of $1710$ and $572964$, the greatest common divisor of $1710$ and $572964$ is $\boxed{22}$. The answer is 22
